3. REVENUE-SHARING MECHANISM

3.1 Mandatory Revenue Sharing — Pay Upward

When a Monetizing Party's Attributable Revenue exceeds the De Minimis
Threshold in a calendar quarter, they must distribute a revenue share to all
Accepting Contributors at every level above them in the Heritage Chain. Payment
flows upward through the tree only. THE ROOT PROJECT (VAPOUR) OWES NO REVENUE
SHARES TO ANYONE.

3.2 Downstream Forks Excluded — Except Registered Fork Contributors

A Monetizing Party does not pay revenue shares to any project or contributor
below them in the Heritage Chain, EXCEPT that Registered Fork Contributors
(Section 3.7) are eligible to receive shares from their own downstream
Monetizing Parties.

3.3 Default Sharing Percentage

The default sharing percentage is ONE PERCENT (1%) of Attributable Revenue per
quarter. This applies unless modified by mutual written agreement of all
Accepting Contributors in the Heritage Chain.

3.4 Distribution Formula

Individual Share = (Attributable Revenue x 1%) / (Total Accepting Contributors
above this project)

Opted-out and non-participating contributors are excluded from the denominator.

3.5 Attribution of Revenue for Bundled Products

Where the Program is one component of a larger product, Attributable Revenue
is determined using one of:

  Method A — Direct Attribution: identify specific revenue streams directly
  generated by the component.

  Method B — Safe Harbor Apportionment: multiply total product Revenue by the
  ratio of (lines of code in the CHL component) to (total lines of code in the
  product), excluding auto-generated code, tests, and third-party libraries.
  Application of this method in good faith with documented inputs creates a
  safe harbor against liability for underreporting.

  Method C — Negotiated Rate: a fixed amount or percentage negotiated in
  writing with a supermajority (two-thirds) of Accepting Contributors, reviewed
  annually.

3.6 Subsidiary and Affiliate Revenue

Revenue of a subsidiary or affiliate is included only if: (a) the subsidiary
directly uses the Program to generate that revenue; and (b) the Monetizing
Party controls or consolidates the subsidiary's financial statements.

3.7 Registered Fork Contributor

A contributor who has made a Substantial Improvement may register by:
(a) submitting a written registration to the Heritage Chain Registry;
(b) providing explicit acceptance of this License per Section 4.5; and
(c) having the registration confirmed by at least one existing Accepting
Contributor, or, failing such confirmation within sixty (60) days, by
uncontested publication in the Registry.

3.8 Distribution Schedule

Distributions must be made quarterly, within forty-five (45) days after the
close of each calendar quarter in which Attributable Revenue exceeds the De
Minimis Threshold.

3.9 Record Keeping

The Monetizing Party shall maintain complete, accurate records of all Revenue
and distributions for no fewer than seven (7) years, available for audit by any
Accepting Contributor within thirty (30) days of written request.


4. OPT-OUT, INDIVIDUAL FORFEITURE, AND ACCEPTANCE

4.1 Voluntary Participation

Participation in revenue sharing is entirely voluntary. Any Verified Contributor
may file an Opt-Out Declaration at any time. An opted-out contributor receives
no distributions and imposes no revenue-sharing payment obligation on their
direct downstream forks with respect to that contributor's share specifically.

4.2 Opt-Out Does Not Break the Chain

An opted-out contributor's position in the Heritage Chain is skipped for
revenue-sharing purposes only. Downstream forks still owe revenue shares to all
Accepting Contributors above the opted-out contributor.

4.3 No All-or-Nothing Rule

THIS LICENSE CONTAINS NO ALL-OR-NOTHING PROVISION. If a contributor does not
accept or cannot be contacted, only that contributor's share is withheld and
redistributed pro rata among all other Accepting Contributors. No single
contributor's refusal or non-response can block distributions owed to others.

4.4 Default Status

A contributor who has neither accepted nor opted out is "non-participating" and
receives no distributions. The Monetizing Party must document outreach attempts
per Section 5.3 but is not in breach if a contributor remains non-responsive
after documented good-faith efforts.

4.5 Acceptance Mechanism

Acceptance must be: (a) in writing or digitally recorded with a verifiable
timestamp; (b) explicitly referencing the Program by name and "CHL v1.3";
(c) retained by the Monetizing Party; and (d) available to any Accepting
Contributor upon request.

4.6 Opt-Out Declaration

To opt out, a contributor files a written declaration identifying themselves,
the Program(s), the scope of opt-out (receiving, imposing, or both), and
duration. A contributor may revoke at any time; revocation takes effect for
distributions in the quarter following receipt of notice. No retroactive
distributions are owed for periods of opt-out.


5. HERITAGE CHAIN TREE — STRUCTURE AND OBLIGATIONS

5.1 Tree Model

  Root (Vapour): Owes nothing. Receives shares from all downstream Monetizing
  Parties — subject to any Opt-Out Declaration filed by Root contributors.

  Branches: Each branch pays all Accepting Contributors above it, up to and
  including the Root.

  Registered Fork Contributors: Eligible to receive shares from all Monetizing
  Parties at or below their level.

5.2 Illustrative Example

Heritage Chain: Vapour (Root) -> Fork A -> Fork B -> Fork C (Monetizing Party).

  Fork C pays Accepting Contributors in: Fork B, Fork A, and Vapour.
  Fork C does NOT pay any project below Fork C.
  If Fork B has opted out, Fork C still pays Fork A and Vapour.
  If Vapour's contributor has opted out (as they currently have), Fork C owes
    no share to Vapour's contributor specifically — but would owe shares to any
    other Accepting Contributors added to the Heritage Chain in the future.
  Vapour (Root) owes no shares to anyone.

5.3 Multiple Upstream Projects

Where a Derivative Work merges code from multiple Upstream Projects, all
Accepting Contributors across all merged upstream branches are included in the
distribution formula.


6. COMPLIANCE — SIMPLIFIED METADATA AND SAFE HARBOR SEARCH

6.1 Single Compliance File

Every distribution or Network Use deployment must include a CHL-COMPLIANCE.json
file at the project root. This single file must contain:
  (a) license version ("CHL v1.3");
  (b) Root Project name and identifier;
  (c) Heritage Chain entries with contributor names, verification method, and
      acceptance/opt-out/registered status;
  (d) Monetizing Party contact information (if applicable);
  (e) for Network Use: URL where Corresponding Source is publicly available.

Human-readable summaries (HERITAGE-CHAIN.md, CONTRIBUTORS.md) are recommended
but not required; failure to include them is not a breach so long as
CHL-COMPLIANCE.json is present and accurate.

6.2 Per-File Notice

Every file in the Program should contain:

  SPDX-License-Identifier: LicenseRef-CHL-1.3
  Copyright (C) 2026 KiwiOnGit
  Source: https://github.com/KiwiOnGit/Vapour

6.3 Safe Harbor Search Procedure

The Monetizing Party's obligation to identify Verified Contributors is satisfied
— and no breach can be based on failure to identify a contributor — if the
Monetizing Party completes and documents the following steps:
  (a) queries the commit log of all public repositories hosting the Program and
      Upstream Projects for contributor names and contact details;
  (b) contacts all contributors with discoverable contact information at least
      once and retries at thirty (30) days;
  (c) publishes a public notice in the primary community channel of the Program
      for at least sixty (60) days; and
  (d) documents steps (a)-(c) in the CHL-COMPLIANCE.json file.

A contributor not discoverable after these steps is treated as non-
participating. No further search obligation arises unless the contributor later
self-identifies.

6.4 Automatic Tooling

The maintainers of this License shall endeavor to maintain open-source tooling
that automates generation of CHL-COMPLIANCE.json from standard version control
repositories. Use of such tooling constitutes a rebuttable presumption of
compliance with Sections 6.1 and 6.3.


7. DISPUTE RESOLUTION AND ADMINISTRATION

7.1 Heritage Chain Registry

The Monetizing Party must maintain or contribute to a public registry containing
the information in CHL-COMPLIANCE.json, including acceptance/opt-out status and
registered fork contributions.

7.2 Notification Requirements

Upon initiating Commercial Use, the Monetizing Party shall, within thirty (30)
days: notify all identified Verified Contributors; provide an explanation of the
Revenue arrangement and this License; provide acceptance and opt-out forms; and
establish a contact mechanism.

7.3 Disputes

Disputes shall be resolved through: (1) good-faith negotiation for at least
thirty (30) days; (2) mediation by a mutually-agreed neutral party; (3) binding
arbitration under JAMS International Arbitration Rules, ICC Rules, or equivalent
mutually agreed rules. Parties are encouraged to agree in advance on an arbitral
seat convenient to both parties.

7.4 International Enforcement

Any arbitral award rendered under Section 7.3 may be enforced in any
jurisdiction that is a signatory to the 1958 New York Convention on the
Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign Arbitral Awards.


